 3473}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "primary human macrophages", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.6076088547706604, "span": {"begin": 3505, "end": 3530}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7498944997787476, "span": {"begin": 3513, "end": 3518}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7097"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TLR2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9927017688751221, "span": {"begin": 3559, "end": 3563}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7099"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TLR4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9894722104072571, "span": {"begin": 3568, "end": 3572}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7096"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TLRs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9746779799461365, "span": {"begin": 3647, "end": 3651}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007249"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "inflammation", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9997740387916565, "span": {"begin": 3685, "end": 3697}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005355"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fibrosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999300241470337, "span": {"begin": 3699, "end": 3707}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7096"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TLRs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9734408259391785, "span": {"begin": 3782, "end": 3786}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011658"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lung fibrosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999353885650635, "span": {"begin": 3812, "end": 3825}}, {"id": ["mesh:D012822"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "silica", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9968284964561462, "span": {"begin": 3878, "end": 3884}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "macrophages", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7706803679466248, "span": {"begin": 3953, "end": 3964}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9286330342292786, "span": {"begin": 3966, "end": 3970}}, {"id": ["mesh:C564245", "mim:608404"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "deficient in class A scavenger macrophage", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.8397322297096252, "span": {"begin": 3971, "end": 4012}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8685"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MARCO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9853876829147339, "span": {"begin": 4050, "end": 4055}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010644"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MARCO", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9065636992454529, "span": {"begin": 4171, "end": 4176}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001761"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "bleomycin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986544847488403, "span": {"begin": 4283, "end": 4292}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010269"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "paraquat", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988407492637634, "span": {"begin": 4294, "end": 4302}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:28786"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "N,N&#39;-dimethyl-4, 4&prime;-bipyridinium dichloride", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9970811009407043, "span": {"begin": 4334, "end": 4387}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lung epithelial cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8309993743896484, "span": {"begin": 4440, "end": 4461}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005355"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fibrosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9969615340232849, "span": {"begin": 4608, "end": 4616}}], "text": "The human lung consists of approximately 40 different resident cell types that play different roles during homeostasis, injury, repair and disease states (Franks et al., 2008; Luettich et al., 2021). Of these, resident airway epithelial cells, alveolar/interstitial macrophages and dendritic cells are well characterised for their ability to sense the danger upon interaction with harmful substances and relay the message to mount the necessary immune/inflammatory response. The resident macrophages are present in all tissues, and in a steady state, macrophages contribute to epithelial integrity, survey the tissue for invading pathogens or chemicals and maintain an immunosuppressive environment. Their main function is to clear the incoming irritants and microbes. They are named differently based on the tissue type and their specific functions (Kierdorf et al., 2015).   Substance interactions:   The chemicals or pathogens interact with cellular membrane to gain access to the organisms&rsquo; interior. A predominant interaction mechanism involves the recognition of innate immune response agonists by pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) present on resident cells such as epithelial and alveolar macrophages. PRRs are also present on other immune and parenchymal cells. PRRs can be activated by two classes of ligands. Pathogen associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) are microbial molecules derived from invading pathogens. PAMPs will not be discussed further as pathogens are not the focus for the AOP 173. The other class of ligands are called danger associated molecular patterns (DAMPs) that include cellular fragments, nucleic acids, small molecules, proteins and even cytokines released from injured or dying cells (Bianchi, 2007). Most&nbsp;stressors discussed in AOP173 act via DAMPs-driven PRR activation. High aspect ratio (HAR) materials such as asbestos or carbon nanotubes (CNTs) pierce the cellular membrane of epithelial cells or resident macrophages resulting in cell injury or non-programmed cellular death. Alveolar macrophages trying to engulf HAR&nbsp;fibres that are long and stiff undergo frustrated phagocytosis because of their inability to engulf the piercing fibres and subsequently lead to cell injury (Boyles et al., 2015; Brown et al., 2007;&nbsp;Donaldson K et al., 2010;&nbsp;D&ouml;rger et al., 2001;&nbsp;Mossman and Churg, 1998). The cellular debris from injured or dying cell then serves as ligands for PRRs (Nakayama, 2018), leading to cell activation. In case of insoluble particles such as silica, coal dust and nanomaterials (NMs), the particle adsorbed opsonins such as immunoglobulins, complement proteins, or serum proteins act as ligands to the receptors on the macrophage cell surface (Behzadi et al., 2017). The tissue response to these materials resembles that observed following foreign body invasion in lungs.   Toll-like receptors (TLRs) are highly conserved PRRs that are engaged by stressors associated with&nbsp;(Desai et al., 2018) tissue inflammation, injury and fibrosis-like response. Inhibition of TLR-4 is protective against bleomycin-induced fibrosis (Li et al., 2015). However, the exact role and mechanisms by which TLRs mediate lung fibrosis are yet to be uncovered and some studies have shown TLRs to be protective against lung fibrosis (Desai et al., 2018). Binding of TLR2 and TLR4 by multiple stressors is shown to activate pro-inflammatory cascade in vivo (Danielsen et al., 2021). In vitro, carbon nanotube-induced activation of primary human macrophages was shown to depend on both TLR2 and TLR4 (Mukherjee et al., 2018). However, the exact role and mechanisms by which TLRs mediate lung response, including inflammation, fibrosis and other lung events are yet to be uncovered and some studies have shown TLRs to be protective against lung fibrosis (Desai et al., 2018; Li et al., 2015). Asbestos and silica crystals are suggested to engage scavenger receptors present on the macrophages. Mice deficient in class A scavenger macrophage receptor with collagenous structure (MARCO) are shown to induce reduced lung response following chrysotile asbestos exposure; although, the direct binding of MARCO by asbestos is not investigated in the study (Murthy et al., 2015). In case of soluble substances such as bleomycin, paraquat (Dinis-Oliveira et al., 2008) (N,N&#39;-dimethyl-4, 4&prime;-bipyridinium dichloride) and other soluble&nbsp;chemicals, direct damage of lung epithelial cells and resulting cellular debris or secreted cytokines (DAMPs) serve as triggers for downstream cascading pro-inflammatory events, tissue injury and fibrosis-like responses. Engagement of PRRs and consequent cell activation is observed in various organisms including flies and mammals (Denholm and Phan, 1990; Matzinger, 2002).", "timestamp": "Wed Jun 24 09:53:21 +0000 2026"}